00:30:06.240 --> 00:30:07.300
or puppies.

00:30:08.150 --> 00:30:09.920
If it's a simple bug fix, that's like cake.

00:30:10.080 --> 00:30:10.720
You'd like, thank you.

00:30:11.750 --> 00:30:12.640
I enjoyed that cake.

00:30:13.720 --> 00:30:16.200
Then move on. But some PRs are like a puppy.

00:30:16.900 --> 00:30:17.900
It's like, it's terrific.

00:30:18.010 --> 00:30:20.440
You like puppies, but you've got to feed them

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:22.260
and clean up after them.

00:30:22.960 --> 00:30:24.340
Why am I standing in the rain

00:30:24.370 --> 00:30:26.300
with this puppy on a Friday night?

00:30:26.580 --> 00:30:27.160
How did I get here?

00:30:27.560 --> 00:30:29.180
Yeah, so sometimes you have to say...

00:30:29.180 --> 00:30:30.160
Collecting the puppies, poof.

00:30:30.440 --> 00:30:31.120
Yeah, exactly.

00:30:31.960 --> 00:30:36.260
Sometimes you say, thank you, but I just can't look after another puppy right now.

00:30:38.080 --> 00:30:40.180
And that's a difficult thing to come to terms with,

00:30:40.330 --> 00:30:41.640
when the project gets a bit more mature.

00:30:43.120 --> 00:30:44.640
Because previously, you're accepting all the puppies.

00:30:45.640 --> 00:30:47.800
But then you have to start saying no to puppies.

00:30:48.940 --> 00:30:51.480
And Rich definitely got there because it accumulated...

00:30:51.500 --> 00:30:53.800
Will, do you hate puppies? Come on, that's a pretty hard stance.

00:30:54.040 --> 00:30:55.920
I'm kind of a cat person, to be honest with you.

00:30:57.360 --> 00:31:00.420
But yeah, I mean, you have to say no eventually.

00:31:00.770 --> 00:31:00.880
Yeah.

00:31:01.300 --> 00:31:06.280
I think this is where plugins always kind of like take the center stage, right?

00:31:06.360 --> 00:31:09.860
You're like, just, oh, that sounds like a great idea for you to maintain external to my library.

00:31:10.400 --> 00:31:13.480
That was exactly my approach to the whole situation.

00:31:13.700 --> 00:31:13.760
Yep.

00:31:15.800 --> 00:31:16.680
Have fun.

00:31:18.680 --> 00:31:24.720
But also the probability of some little change breaking someone's code and like being considered

00:31:24.740 --> 00:31:29.100
a breaking change grows as the project grows in usage.

00:31:29.340 --> 00:31:33.200
And like, you know, like at some point it's like almost any change

00:31:33.380 --> 00:31:36.720
will end up breaking someone in very unexpected ways

00:31:36.940 --> 00:31:39.160
because they are doing something really, really weird,

00:31:39.240 --> 00:31:40.880
but you know, like someone is doing it.

00:31:41.240 --> 00:31:44.920
So like it becomes more and more difficult to know,

00:31:44.980 --> 00:31:47.220
like is this a breaking change or not?

00:31:47.280 --> 00:31:51.320
Like no one should be using this variable here or this parameter,

00:31:51.500 --> 00:31:53.920
but like, you know, there's someone out there doing that.

00:31:54.180 --> 00:32:06.000
So I don't know, I feel defining what is actually a breaking change and what is a strict sember gets more difficult as things grow.

00:32:06.490 --> 00:32:07.020
Yeah, I don't know.

00:32:08.160 --> 00:32:13.900
One of the things I like that the Django project did was kind of basically only things that are documented are supported, basically.

00:32:14.050 --> 00:32:18.340
That was kind of the line they drew, and I thought that was a pretty good way to draw it.

00:32:18.400 --> 00:32:20.100
But yeah, that never actually works.

00:32:20.190 --> 00:32:21.000
That doesn't make people happy.

00:32:21.090 --> 00:32:23.180
It just gives you plausible deniability.

00:32:24.620 --> 00:32:25.160
Don't yell at me.

00:32:25.550 --> 00:32:26.220
It's not my fault.

00:32:26.970 --> 00:32:29.760
Yeah, I think adding a formal versioning policy

00:32:29.980 --> 00:32:31.500
is one of the best things that we did.

00:32:31.840 --> 00:32:34.440
Because for a long time, Ruff was just,

00:32:34.570 --> 00:32:35.740
we only used patch releases.

00:32:35.990 --> 00:32:39.060
So we got to like 0, 0, like 285 or something.

00:32:41.300 --> 00:32:43.800
And we had basically no guarantees

00:32:44.180 --> 00:32:46.380
about what would or wouldn't change across releases.

00:32:47.560 --> 00:32:50.500
And as the project got more and more popular,

00:32:50.660 --> 00:32:52.220
that started to cause more and more problems.

00:32:52.660 --> 00:32:56.080
And so Zany, someone on our team, like when they joined, one of the first few things they

00:32:56.080 --> 00:32:58.680
did was like create an actual formal versioning policy.

00:32:58.860 --> 00:33:00.820
And we added like preview behavior.

00:33:01.060 --> 00:33:05.860
So like you can opt similar to what Black has and kind of opt into like breaking or more

00:33:06.180 --> 00:33:06.860
experimental changes.

00:33:07.600 --> 00:33:11.020
And so now we have like clear expectations around what it means to like bump a minor release,

00:33:11.260 --> 00:33:11.920
et cetera, et cetera.

00:33:12.060 --> 00:33:16.880
And like that has made our lives a lot easier, like actually having clear expectations around

00:33:17.060 --> 00:33:18.400
that that are communicated and respected.

00:33:19.960 --> 00:33:24.600
But it's the kind of thing that you just don't think about at all until it, at least I didn't, until the Ratchet got bigger.

00:33:26.500 --> 00:33:26.900
Yeah.

00:33:27.140 --> 00:33:32.720
Some people's code runs things like FastAPI or Octoprint or whatever.

00:33:33.460 --> 00:33:35.600
Your stuff rewrites people's code.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:37.180
Yeah.

00:33:37.250 --> 00:33:38.520
But it doesn't run at runtime.

00:33:38.890 --> 00:33:39.260
I don't know.

00:33:39.300 --> 00:33:40.160
I actually think it's easier.

00:33:43.560 --> 00:33:43.780
Yeah.

00:33:45.260 --> 00:33:45.480
Indeed.

00:33:45.560 --> 00:33:51.400
I mean, it's like, it's funny you talk about the plugins thing. Cause like,

00:33:52.620 --> 00:33:56.800
I've actually very intentionally taken the opposite approach, which is we have like almost no public API

00:33:57.940 --> 00:34:03.380
because like the only public API is the CLI and like, we don't expose our API in any other way.

00:34:04.760 --> 00:34:09.020
And that's because like, we know we're going to change like everything internally, like pretty

00:34:09.139 --> 00:34:12.679
dramatically. And so we wanted to have like full control over that without having to worry about

00:34:12.700 --> 00:34:13.639
breaking people's stuff yet.

00:34:15.159 --> 00:34:16.780
But it's starting to become more of a problem

00:34:17.050 --> 00:34:18.780
because more and more people want to use it as a library

00:34:18.970 --> 00:34:19.659
in different ways.

00:34:20.560 --> 00:34:22.280
But it's-- I don't know.

00:34:22.340 --> 00:34:24.379
It's sort of a counterintuitive way

00:34:24.409 --> 00:34:26.940
to make our lives easier as maintainers

00:34:26.950 --> 00:34:30.100
was not expose any public API apart from the CLI.

00:34:30.460 --> 00:34:30.960
Yeah, yeah.

00:34:31.280 --> 00:34:31.620
Very interesting.

00:34:32.260 --> 00:34:34.760
Fully, funny sort of anecdote.

00:34:35.300 --> 00:34:38.540
I'm rewriting a lot of the documentation for SQL model

00:34:39.169 --> 00:34:40.340
because I want to have examples.

00:34:40.960 --> 00:34:43.840
Right now I have examples that are compatible with Python 3.7 and about,

00:34:44.540 --> 00:34:45.600
but actually 3.6 and about.

00:34:45.899 --> 00:34:49.760
But I want to have also the syntax for 3.9 and 3.10.

00:34:49.899 --> 00:34:53.740
In 3.10 you can have like the unions using the vertical bar and these things,

00:34:53.760 --> 00:34:55.280
and I want to have examples for each one of those.

00:34:55.800 --> 00:34:59.640
So the approach I did was to write a script that will automatically update

00:34:59.980 --> 00:35:03.060
each one of the files by calling rough as a soup process.

00:35:03.560 --> 00:35:04.380
So that's the API.

00:35:06.300 --> 00:35:08.700
And then like, you know, like doing all that stuff.

00:35:08.900 --> 00:35:11.080
Like, yeah, like another, another.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:12.360
Yeah, great.

00:35:29.560 --> 00:35:30.040
That's

00:35:38.900 --> 00:35:41.280
in the end, unfortunately.

00:35:42.040 --> 00:35:44.200
Yeah, they'll find the underscore functions

00:35:44.500 --> 00:35:46.440
you've tried to dissuade them from using

00:35:46.680 --> 00:35:47.700
and all the things, yeah.

00:35:49.440 --> 00:35:52.440
Eric, what's the origin story for Read the Docs

00:35:52.440 --> 00:35:54.560
and what'd you try and how do you think it caught on?

00:35:55.260 --> 00:35:58.360
Yeah, so, I mean, this was kind of way back in the day,

00:35:58.500 --> 00:36:00.640
but yeah, I kind of got started writing Django plugins,

00:36:01.200 --> 00:36:02.660
you know, apropos to the conversation.

00:36:03.520 --> 00:36:06.200
You know, I was working at the Lawrence Journal World

00:36:06.400 --> 00:36:07.520
where Django came from

00:36:07.620 --> 00:36:08.740
and it was kind of early in my career.

00:36:08.860 --> 00:36:15.640
And I was just kind of getting excited about open source and blogging and just basically built a few of these kind of testing related open source projects.

00:36:16.480 --> 00:36:18.920
And then that was kind of where I got started with open source.

00:36:19.190 --> 00:36:22.180
And then basically it was the classic scratch scratch on itch thing, right?

00:36:22.360 --> 00:36:24.620
Like it's like, I have a bunch of open source projects.

00:36:24.650 --> 00:36:25.800
I want to write documentation.

00:36:26.840 --> 00:36:27.760
How do I solve that problem?

00:36:28.200 --> 00:36:31.100
And back in the day, that was a much harder problem to solve, right?

00:36:31.110 --> 00:36:36.200
It was basically just like build a zip file and upload it to packages.python.org.

00:36:36.430 --> 00:36:37.720
If folks remember that one.

00:36:38.820 --> 00:36:43.100
or was it packages or whatever the docs, there was a docs hosting on PyPI basically.

00:36:44.120 --> 00:36:47.180
And yeah, basically just wanted to kind of build a better version of that, that

00:36:47.960 --> 00:36:48.560
integrated with GitHub.

00:36:48.720 --> 00:36:52.600
I feel like webhooks were like the cool new thing back in 2010, you know?

00:36:53.420 --> 00:36:55.200
And so that was really kind of the insight, right?

00:36:55.280 --> 00:36:58.800
It's like, let's build this kind of like CI, CD workflow on top of webhooks.

00:36:59.320 --> 00:37:03.640
And actually did build a kind of a version of that the previous year around kind of like

00:37:03.760 --> 00:37:04.360
code quality stuff.

00:37:04.700 --> 00:37:10.440
So it actually ran kind of like a linter and built a website on commit and had a similar kind of workflow, right?

00:37:10.600 --> 00:37:14.980
Where it like gave you a grade and did all this kind of stuff, which is like 2009.

00:37:15.820 --> 00:37:17.660
And yeah, that didn't really catch on at all.

00:37:17.700 --> 00:37:19.800
But then I think Read the Docs, just we built it.

00:37:19.900 --> 00:37:21.920
And then I was using it for my own projects.

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:25.360
And I actually had the need to kind of maintain it and keep it updated.

00:37:25.500 --> 00:37:29.760
And then I think people just kind of grew naturally, you know, gave some conference talks, that kind of stuff.

00:37:29.980 --> 00:37:32.220
But I think it just solved a problem that people had.

00:37:32.460 --> 00:37:35.460
And that's always going to be the best way to grow a thing.

00:37:36.200 --> 00:37:36.940
Yeah, absolutely.

00:37:37.430 --> 00:37:37.540
Awesome.

00:37:38.620 --> 00:37:39.820
What's Read the Docs written in?

00:37:39.830 --> 00:37:40.280
Is it Django?

00:37:41.120 --> 00:37:41.240
Yep.

00:37:41.640 --> 00:37:42.920
Yeah, it's all Django and Python.

00:37:44.180 --> 00:37:44.520
Right on.

00:37:45.260 --> 00:37:46.100
Funny coincidence.

00:37:46.370 --> 00:37:50.340
I went to college in Lawrence at the University of Kansas.

00:37:50.720 --> 00:37:51.120
Oh, nice.

00:37:51.500 --> 00:37:58.560
I was right there, right at the heart of Django, but I moved off to grad school a couple years before all that happened.

00:37:58.800 --> 00:38:00.960
So I missed the excitement.

00:38:00.980 --> 00:38:15.140
I grew up in Virginia and everyone's like, you're going to Kansas? You graduated school? How are you going there? Everybody thought it was the weirdest decision, but yeah, I really do think ending up in that Python and Django ecosystem has been pretty transformative to my life.

00:38:16.900 --> 00:38:29.720
Lawrence is a pretty cool little town, actually, of all the places. Sebastian, how did you come about this crazy idea to put types into our web apps? Python, that's dynamic. It doesn't have types. What are you doing?

00:38:30.200 --> 00:38:32.540
Yeah, I don't know. So crazy.

00:38:33.600 --> 00:38:35.960
It's so fun to see Michael Darson in the chat.

00:38:37.060 --> 00:38:41.900
They maintain our URL D3 and the Python security developer in Resilience,

00:38:42.030 --> 00:38:44.140
just chatting along with us.

00:38:44.330 --> 00:38:48.060
He probably has had to deal with so much stuff as us.

00:38:49.040 --> 00:38:49.980
Yeah, I'm sure.

00:38:52.060 --> 00:38:54.620
So some of the first things that I did in open source

00:38:54.650 --> 00:38:57.700
were actually Docker images for deploying Flask

00:38:58.860 --> 00:39:00.060
because I was working with Flask.

00:39:00.420 --> 00:39:03.220
And deploying Flask was difficult,

00:39:03.640 --> 00:39:06.720
and I needed to be able to combine Nginx with UWSGI

00:39:06.940 --> 00:39:07.700
and a bunch of things.

00:39:07.760 --> 00:39:11.060
And they all had their own custom configuration files,

00:39:11.080 --> 00:39:12.420
and it was so difficult.

00:39:13.220 --> 00:39:14.460
I didn't like doing that,

00:39:14.980 --> 00:39:17.800
and then I just had to study how to do that stuff.

00:39:17.920 --> 00:39:19.560
And then after going through all that,

00:39:19.660 --> 00:39:22.580
I wanted to save everyone else's time doing that.

00:39:22.900 --> 00:39:25.840
So it was like, let's just put a Docker image with this

00:39:26.260 --> 00:39:28.900
and a lot of documentation of how this Docker image works

00:39:29.160 --> 00:39:31.800
and how you can use it with some sensible defaults.

00:39:31.820 --> 00:39:33.740
So, you know, it was just like a weird contraption.

00:39:34.200 --> 00:39:34.740
That was it.

00:39:35.260 --> 00:39:38.340
But it actually grew and got like a few stars,

00:39:38.660 --> 00:39:39.460
like a bunch of stars.

00:39:39.540 --> 00:39:41.600
For me, it was a lot, you know, like 100 stars.

00:39:41.720 --> 00:39:43.880
Oh my gosh, I'm an open source developer.

00:39:45.580 --> 00:39:46.400
And then like at some point,

00:39:46.420 --> 00:39:48.160
it had like a thousand stars or something like that.

00:39:48.160 --> 00:39:49.520
I was so happy about that.

00:39:49.800 --> 00:39:52.140
And at some point, it was kind of the de facto standard

00:39:52.320 --> 00:39:55.580
for doing Flask in Docker.

00:39:55.640 --> 00:39:58.000
that was the first thing that I did.

00:39:59.200 --> 00:40:00.980
I ended up with FastAPI.

00:40:01.060 --> 00:40:03.540
I was avoiding building FastAPI for a long while,

00:40:03.680 --> 00:40:05.660
and I was trying all the other frameworks

00:40:05.840 --> 00:40:06.520
and all the other tools.

00:40:07.220 --> 00:40:08.580
I was convinced that there was something

00:40:08.640 --> 00:40:10.600
that would do the things that I wanted.

00:40:10.820 --> 00:40:11.860
I just had to find it.

00:40:12.920 --> 00:40:14.580
And as I was trying different frameworks,

00:40:15.020 --> 00:40:15.900
also in different languages,

00:40:16.280 --> 00:40:19.880
I was extending the list of things that I wanted to have

00:40:20.480 --> 00:40:22.920
and also the list of things that I wanted not to have.

00:40:23.080 --> 00:40:24.200
For example, I didn't want to...

00:40:24.220 --> 00:40:26.900
That takes you farther and farther away from any framework.

00:40:27.460 --> 00:40:27.700
Exactly.

00:40:27.700 --> 00:40:29.760
Having one that will tick all the boxes.

00:40:30.120 --> 00:40:30.820
So it was like, ah.

00:40:31.990 --> 00:40:33.920
But then I realized, I really like

00:40:34.020 --> 00:40:35.760
this thing of having types, as in types

00:40:35.920 --> 00:40:37.900
because you get out of completion and inline errors.

00:40:38.210 --> 00:40:39.000
And this is so cool.

00:40:39.080 --> 00:40:40.300
It's so cool to be able to have this.

00:40:40.760 --> 00:40:42.140
I want to have this in Python.

00:40:42.340 --> 00:40:43.860
And then Python added type annotations.

00:40:43.930 --> 00:40:45.180
And it was like, this is great.

00:40:45.940 --> 00:40:46.640
How do I use them?

00:40:46.740 --> 00:40:48.680
There's no way to use them with the current frameworks.

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:52.520
So at some point, I actually found the right framework.

00:40:52.720 --> 00:40:55.840
It was called API Star by the same author of Django REST framework.

00:40:56.640 --> 00:40:59.240
And it was just missing some authentication stuff.

00:40:59.340 --> 00:41:01.600
I said, like, okay, I'm going to contribute to the other stuff.

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:05.500
When I was about to jump into the code, he said, I have to deprecate this.

00:41:05.700 --> 00:41:08.060
I will go focus full on Starlet.

00:41:09.260 --> 00:41:10.540
And then he went to build Starlet.

00:41:10.580 --> 00:41:15.560
This is Tom Christie, which is super prolific and an amazing open source person in general.

00:41:16.840 --> 00:41:22.080
And then at that point is when I said, like, ah, I just have to try it.

00:41:22.180 --> 00:41:22.600
Let's just do it.

00:41:23.260 --> 00:41:31.040
So I'm just going to try to build something that will be kind of a spiritual successor to API Star, built on top of Starlet.

00:41:31.690 --> 00:41:41.300
So I was, you know, like I was actually narrating all the learnings from Flask, Django, Django REST framework and all the ecosystem and just like bringing all those ideas together.

00:41:41.580 --> 00:41:45.800
At least that was my intention. And then I wanted to have a bit of better type annotations.

00:41:45.820 --> 00:41:49.120
So I saw that Pydantic was using standard type of notation.

00:41:49.260 --> 00:41:51.380
So people wouldn't have to learn this, like, you know,

00:41:51.600 --> 00:41:54.200
from past API for special string or something like that.

00:41:54.380 --> 00:41:56.240
Just instead of that, just use pure string.

00:41:56.860 --> 00:41:58.980
So I wanted to have something based on standards,

00:41:59.580 --> 00:42:01.620
like OpenAPI, JSON schema, and all that stuff.

00:42:02.260 --> 00:42:03.460
And based on standard Python,

00:42:03.600 --> 00:42:06.040
and to have like the simplest syntax possible

00:42:06.380 --> 00:42:09.440
and to, you know, like give the best developer experience possible

00:42:10.140 --> 00:42:15.780
while, you know, like not adding like any additional steps

00:42:15.800 --> 00:42:19.960
for developers to build something that by default will have all the best practices built in.

00:42:20.480 --> 00:42:21.560
That was the intention.

00:42:22.080 --> 00:42:25.340
And I was just like trying to solve it for the things that I was working on.

00:42:25.540 --> 00:42:28.460
I was supposed to be doing AI and machine learning and stuff,

00:42:28.740 --> 00:42:33.020
but like I had to stop for a bit to solve APIs and I got stuck in APIs.

00:42:33.800 --> 00:42:35.440
And that's how I ended up with FastAPI.

00:42:35.860 --> 00:42:38.080
Oh, I think you made a pretty decent choice.

00:42:38.140 --> 00:42:39.840
It seems like FastAPI is doing all right.

00:42:40.620 --> 00:42:40.980
Yeah.

00:42:41.820 --> 00:42:42.560
Yeah, I just saw you.

00:42:42.920 --> 00:42:45.220
Much better than what I ever had expected.

00:42:45.680 --> 00:42:46.460
Yeah, I know. Congratulations.

00:42:47.120 --> 00:42:47.960
Well, it's also deserved.

00:42:48.860 --> 00:42:53.820
But I also just saw an X, I don't know, a post on X Twitter,

00:42:54.360 --> 00:42:56.240
however you address these things,

00:42:56.820 --> 00:42:58.900
where you said you showed a graph

00:42:59.440 --> 00:43:03.380
where the number of GitHub stars for FastAPI just passed Flask.

00:43:03.510 --> 00:43:07.900
And I have a lot of respect for Flask and the Palette team

00:43:08.120 --> 00:43:09.620
and David Lord and all those folks.

00:43:09.920 --> 00:43:13.060
But awesome that your stuff has taken off so much.

00:43:13.160 --> 00:43:13.480
That's really cool.

00:43:13.600 --> 00:43:15.320
It's super cool. It's amazing.

00:43:15.560 --> 00:43:19.540
And Flask was one of the big inspirations for FastAPI.

00:43:19.590 --> 00:43:22.820
And I've been able to be at this point.

00:43:22.940 --> 00:43:23.560
It's crazy.

00:43:23.730 --> 00:43:29.140
Like, yeah, I still can't get over it.

00:43:29.740 --> 00:43:30.420
Yeah, super cool.

00:43:30.500 --> 00:43:31.960
Super cool to be able to build all this

00:43:31.970 --> 00:43:33.480
and to keep building more stuff.

